## Section 1 — Database Migration

### 1.1 Update `gvs_saved_growth_scenarios` — Forced Unique Save Logic

Add a unique constraint that prevents a scenario from being resaved under the same name if any input metric has changed. The uniqueness is enforced at the database level on a combination of `user_id`, `scenario_name`, and a hash of the `inputs` JSONB.

```sql
-- Add input hash column for uniqueness enforcement
ALTER TABLE public.gvs_saved_growth_scenarios
  ADD COLUMN inputs_hash text GENERATED ALWAYS AS (
    encode(sha256(inputs::text::bytea), 'hex')
  ) STORED;

-- Unique constraint: same user cannot save two scenarios
-- with the same name AND the same input configuration
CREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_gvs_saved_unique_name_inputs
  ON public.gvs_saved_growth_scenarios (user_id, scenario_name, inputs_hash);
```

**Behavioral implication for frontend:** Before saving, if a record exists with the same `user_id`, `scenario_name`, and `inputs_hash`, Supabase returns a unique constraint violation. The frontend must catch this and prompt: "A scenario with this name and configuration already exists. Choose a different name or modify your inputs." If the inputs have changed but the name is the same, the constraint allows the save because `inputs_hash` will differ — this is a new scenario, not an overwrite.

